Document: Logging
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/logging.rst
Summary: Overview of how to use the print and push_error/warning functions for debugging in Godot.

Godot provides several functions for logging information to the console during development. These are essential for debugging and monitoring the state of your application.

The primary function for outputting text to the console is print(). This function accepts any number of arguments and converts them to strings, printing them to the standard output.

GDScript:
    print("Hello, world!")
    var score = 100
    print("Current score: ", score)

C#:
    GD.Print("Hello, world!");
    int score = 100;
    GD.Print("Current score: ", score);

For more specific diagnostic information, Godot provides functions that categorize messages. These messages appear in the Debugger tab's Errors panel and are often highlighted in different colors.

push_warning(message: String)
This function logs a warning message. Warnings do not stop the execution of the game but indicate that something might be wrong or unexpected.

push_error(message: String)
This function logs an error message. Errors indicate a failure in the application logic. When an error is pushed, Godot will also print a stack trace to help identify where the error occurred.

GDScript:
    if player_health < 0:
        push_warning("Player health is negative!")

    if not file.is_open():
        push_error("Failed to open file.")

C#:
    if (playerHealth < 0)
    {
        GD.PushWarning("Player health is negative!");
    }

    if (!file.IsOpen())
    {
        GD.PushError("Failed to open file.");
    }

Key Rule: Use print() for general information, push_warning() for non-critical issues that should be addressed, and push_error() for critical failures that prevent expected behavior.

When running the project from the editor, these logs appear in the Output panel at the bottom of the screen. You can filter these logs by type (Errors, Warnings, or Standard Output) using the buttons provided in the Debugger interface. Note: In exported projects, these logs are typically redirected to a file or the system console depending on the platform and project settings.
